and there are so many more variations of DEs in Linux, compared to BSD Unix, for example.
 
this is not specifically about one license or another.  just examples.

so the project winds up existing within a silo made up of that chosen license.

i mean, there's gotta be a reason so many devs prefer GPLv2 over BSD license for example, as desktop and server Linux is thriving, and seeking out active installations of BSD Unix becomes a challenge.

so if you have a group of devs that are averse to a certain license, and they see your project falls under that license, they're likely to avoid the project. likely because they intend on recycling the code to be used elsewhere that might conflict with the license.

does the license one chooses for a project wind up becoming a trap?

once you start with a selected license, and ask for contributions to code under that license, it becomes a self-perpetuating web under that license, and becomes seemingly impossible to move out from under it.

GoPros fail in uncomfortable heat. use a cover with vent holes over the battery door and on top (above camera, next to Record button).

recent GoPros are waterproof. avoid using MediaMod kit which breaches the seals.

GoPros fail in extreme cold.  the workaround is to jack up the quality so the camera warms up. the batteries reduce power in the cold, by half, so shoot shorter segments, swap batteries sooner.

from my perspective, running on a tight budget, an Intel NUC is great when it's discounted this deeply. honestly, i wouldn't have gotten one at its normal going price.

sure, i found it for around $80, but that was dumb luck, chance.

most NUCs of this model go for around $200-$250, & often without storage or RAM.

yes, a Pi 4 kit & all the needed parts can reach that price, but also a Pi 4 lacks many apps, due to it running an ARM processor.

i keep thinking in terms of comparing this to something like a Raspberry Pi 4 being used as a desktop, and i think the one main advantage this has over the Pi 4 is apps. every x86 app is available on an Intel based NUC.

but here is where the difficulty sets in:  price
i'm running Ubuntu Ubuntu 20.04 LTS on it, with preload and zram swap enabled, and it runs fairly well, handling Chrome browser and its web apps pretty easily.
